In response to current market conditions, concerns around the solvency of global exchanges and passive income yield platforms, we would like to clarify some of the questions raised by our users. 
 
In the first instance, as a business, we are not authorised to
provide legal or financial advice: we recommend that all users seek independent advice with respect to their financial, tax and legal objectives and obligations in line with their personal circumstances.
 
Financial products, including those issued by traditional
licensed financial intuitions such as banks and mutual funds are accompanied by various legal documents that are designed to bind and protect the interest of all parties; these can include terms & conditions, privacy and data protection policies, product disclosure statements and private placement memoranda to name a few.
 
Yielding products and/or loans typically remunerate purchasers with a fixed or variable rate of interest adjusted to reflect the underlying risk of the asset class, business, or products of the issuer, including insolvency.
 
Where such an event occurs, a solvency process is initiated which is governed by the entity and jurisdiction in which the creditor has
contracted the services or products. Insolvency practices vary from country to country but in practice follow the same general principles, which include defining the seniority of the creditors: secured creditors can consist of lenders with a charge over assets, including real estate and other immovable property, commercial pledges and different types of preferential treatment based on share ownership, the respective revenue or tax office and so on. 
 
In the event that a business becomes insolvent, secured debtors would receive proceeds from the disposal of assets held by a company
less the expense cost of the insolvency administration. The value of the
remaining assets would then be apportioned to the unsecured creditors and returned by the administrator, after which the company would be struck off.
 
In the case of an Estonian entity, foreign creditors are treated equally alongside domestic creditors and loans to directors and shareholders are treated as subordinated debt. In the case of Yield App on a
consolidated group basis, as at 11th April 2022, the total value of liabilities
owed to secured creditors is $310,245; there are currently no tax liabilities or loans to shareholders or directors.
 
We understand the challenges and potential impacts that volatile
market conditions present, we continue to operate as per our internal policies and risk governance frameworks that have been implemented to protect the business, its partners, customers and respective service providers.
